		<LI>If you missed the Testing Web Applications with Spring 3.2 Webinar with  Sam Brannen and Rossen Stoyanchev, <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=K6x8LE7Qd1Q">you can see it in HD</a> on YouTube.</LI>
  <LI> Nicolas Frankel put together a post that demonstrates how to change the default scope of beans. Beans are singleton scoped if no scope is otherwise specified.  This example uses a Spring framework  <CODE>BeanFactoryPostProcessor</CODE> to achieve the effect.   NB: this is  <EM>not</EM> something I'd recommend doing! This is <EM>super</EM> hackety. It is, however, a nice illustration of just how flexible Spring is.  </LI>
 <LI>   Petri Kainulainen put together <A href="http://t.co/vsZ13ubt">a nice tutorial on configuring Spring Data Solr</a>.</LI>
<LI>   CORS, or cross-origin resource sharing is a technique for communicating across hosts, sidestepping the  single-host   policy limitations typical of Ajax communication.  Spring MVC doesn't support it out of the box, but <a href="http://extjs-tutorials.blogspot.com/2013/02/enable-cors-in-spring-mvc-rest-api-for.html">it's easy to add to an existing application, as this tutorial explains</a>. 
	 
 </LI>

 

<LI> The <A href="http://www.agitech.co.uk/quickly-creating-a-simple-spring-mvc-application/">Agitech Limited blog has an introduction to Spring MVC tutorial</a> that you might find interesting. 
